ough science. With particular attention to quantum theory, natural science, technoscience, and a section devoted specifically to investigating what Being and Time has to say about science, the book will be of interest to scholars in a wide range of disciplines and traditions. It closes with consideration of questions about sustainability and ethics raised by Heidegger's engagement with the sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Heidegger. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Science. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / General.2bisacsh1 aBabich, Babette E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehme, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaputo, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCerbone, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrease, Robert P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazebrook, Trish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazebrook, Trish, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuzzoni, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatab, Lawrence J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeelan, Patrick A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKisiel, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, S. J., William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichter, Ewald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStenstad, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, James R., econtributor.4c